Subsidy Trap
Cambridge, USA—No policy has pitted good economics so directly against good politics as food and energy subsidies do.
Unaffordable subsidies are becoming a core issue faced by the three most important new leaders in the world. They are Egyptian President Sisi, Indonesian President Joko Widodo, and Indian Prime Minister Modi.
Sisi's subsidy cuts may be better than expected.
On the other hand, Modi is facing a worse-than-expected situation, and may even be able to destroy the long-awaited WTO agreement.
While Joko faces a situation that is still unclear.
In July, Sisi completed an achievement that few leaders in North Africa and the Middle East could achieve: he drastically reduced the long-existing energy subsidies, causing prices to rise by 41-78%.
It is strange that almost no anti-protest demonstrations took place.
Egypt's food subsidy plan costs over $5 billion annually and urgently needs reform.
The price of bread has been kept at an extremely low level, often being fed to animals.
In the past, efforts by North African countries to reduce such subsidies often triggered unrest and even overthrew the government.
But the Sisi government seems to have made progress in this area as well.
Bread subsidies have been reduced by 13%.
Sisi had no choice.
Nearly as a result of the reduction in subsidies, the current government's budget deficit target for the next fiscal year still reached 10% of GDP (14% if not reduced in subsidies).
However, few people anticipated that Sisi, who took office in a tumultuous political environment, would act more quickly than Modi.
In Indonesia, newly elected Joko Widodo inherited the long-existing fuel subsidy of 21 billion dollars per year, equivalent to 20% of the government's spending, which has been a heavy burden on the country.
Suharto's successor, Sutiyoso, took a brave step of increasing fuel prices a year ago.
Joko's advisors recommended cutting the remaining subsidies, and he openly said that he plans to implement them gradually within four years.
Economists confidently oppose commodity subsidies, because the agricultural and energy markets are nearly perfectly competitive, with abundant consumers on the demand side and abundant producers on the supply side.
In the imperfectly competitive fields, the government -- not the large private monopolies -- is the root.
Critics of the invisible hand point out that self-regulating private markets may malfunction in various ways.
For example, income inequality and environmental externalities are the two main reasons for government intervention.
The subsidies for food and fossil fuels spark controversy precisely because they are often promoted under the banners of the environment or equality, but in fact, they bring no benefit to these goals, and often have the opposite effect.
The food subsidy in Egypt only provides less than 20% to the poor.
Most countries' gasoline subsidies have enriched the middle class, while the poor rely on walking or public transportation.
In India, only about 0.1% of liquefied petroleum gas subsidies went to the poorest population, while 52.6% flowed into the pockets of the richest groups.
Globally, less than 20% of fossil fuel subsidies went to the poorest 20% of the population.
Food and energy subsidies may also distort public policy, such as Modi's government which aims to protect Indian agricultural subsidies.
In fact, Modi's government vetoed WTO compromise, which destroyed the most important progress in multilateral trade talks in over a decade.
Agricultural subsidies sometimes benefit consumers, especially in poor countries; at other times, they benefit producers, especially in wealthy countries.
India's policy aims to strike a balance between the two.
As a result, India has achieved a remarkable feat: providing wheat to consumers at low prices through government procurement, while also dealing with over-supply because farmers can get high prices.
(Farmers also receive subsidies on input products — electricity, water, and fertilizers — which harm the environment.
) The government purchases large quantities of rotten rice and wheat, and the way consumers receive a small part of it is both corrupt and does not meet the goal of helping the poor.
Government may continue to maintain subsidies and stockpiling.
However, it knows that this will violate the rules of the World Trade Organization.
Since it cannot permanently change these rules, Modi simply vetoed the Trade Facilitation Agreement that the World Trade Organization was eagerly looking forward to.
Once the subsidies are implemented, it's hard to retract them.
When global commodity prices rise (as in the past decade), citizens accustomed to domestic prices determined by the market are more likely to accept the reality that officials cannot isolate them from the shock.
But people accustomed to government-determined food and energy prices will ask the government to be responsible.
This constitutes a very strong reason that subsidies should not be implemented from the beginning.
But this does not mean that once subsidies are implemented, maintaining subsidies will always be the best choice for shrewd politicians.
If the alternative to price increases is shortages or rationing, angry opponents may also erupt.
Similarly, if the continuously widening gap eventually leads to further retail price hikes, slow-moving leaders will not benefit either.
In the ideal situation, while cutting food and energy subsidies, other more effective measures to support low-income earners should be taken.
Developing countries have gained rich experience in effective transfer mechanisms, such as Mexico's Progress-Opportunity Program (Progresa-Oportunidades) and Brazil's Family Allowance Program (Bolsa Família) and other conditional cash transfer policies, and India's Unique Identification system and other technological innovations.
But some countries were forced to adjust when they encountered a budget crisis and may not have enough money to transfer to alleviate the pain.
Clever politicians should perhaps implement the unpopular adjustments from the outset of their rule.
Joko and Sisi both adopted this policy.
Narendra Modi, who won a landslide victory in the election with the slogan of market reform, has fallen behind.
